The zoom idea I like. I may well start looking into this sort of stuff 
myself, not for a while though.

&gt;&gt;Another less well formed idea is to think of how nature deals with the
&gt;&gt;high input space from our own eyes. A large amount of image processing
&gt;&gt;occurs which reduces the high input space information down to the
&gt;&gt;position and size of lines, boundaries and objects. Perhaps we could
&gt;&gt;convert the normal x by y grid state into a more digestable form using a
&gt;&gt;similar technique. E.g. in Go lines of pieces are quite important, so
&gt;&gt;perhaps we could provide the network with data describing where lines are.
&gt;&gt;    
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt;That&#39;s an interesting idea.  But it&#39;s not just lines that are
&gt;important in Go, but *life*, stable structures that are incapable of
&gt;being completely surrounded and captured.  The problem is, recognizing
&gt;live groups of stones, and distinguishing them from dead groups is an
&gt;extremely difficult problem.  To follow your idea, one type of network
&gt;could analyze life/death, and feed that analysis into another network
&gt;that makes game play decisions.
&gt;  
